				<p><strong><em>A Visceral Manipulation Pioneer</em></strong><br />
					Early in his career as a practitioner Jean-Pierre Barral started to manipulate the organs, In 1972 he and Pierre Mercier started using ultrasound and X-rays to observe the movements of the organs. Thanks to Radiologist Doctor Serge Cohen they were able to show and confirm that the organs of the abdominopelvic cavity were in perpetual movements with very precise axes and directions.</p>
				<p><strong><em>Numerous Dissections</em></strong><br />
					It's always important to try to objectify what the hand feels. Jean-Pierre Barral had the wonderful opportunity to work with Professor Georges Arnaud and Doctor Pierre Roulet at Center Hospital at the University of Grenoble, Pneumology Section. There he was able to perform numerous dissections during which he noticed that after therapeutical pneumothorax or surgery certain pleuro-pulmonary scars could create a large mechanical tension on the cervico-pleural attachments. These tensions literally deformed the transverse processes.</p>
				<p>The fact that a bone could be deform due to a mechanical tension created by an organ confirmed to him the importance of releasing the attachment of the organ. At this time, it was a revolutionary. Jean-Pierre Barral remembers he took him two years to prove he could mobilize a kidney. It was not easy to prove it in front of very competent doctors and colleagues. Happily, thanks to ultrasounds, X-rays, and dissections, he was able to show them and they were convinced. It's typically difficult to fight against preconceived ideas. Little by little he has checked all the organs and found how to restore their mobilities. When an organ has is full mobility it is able to assume its full function and also allows the associated joints to recover their amplitudes.</p>
				<p>Visceral Manipulation is now an official part of osteopathy training, and we can say Jean-Pierre Barral has been one of the great promoters and developers of Visceral Manipulation.</p>
				<p><strong><em>A Long Practice</em></strong><br />
					<img src="images/jpb01.jpg" alt="" name="img_jpb01" width="300" height="400" class="alignright" id="img_jpb01" />In a manual profession, clinical practice is the most important thing, and it's thanks to the thousands patients Barral has treated that he was able to develop, test and perfect new techniques. Osteopathy is above all else a profession of hands. &quot;We must thank our patients, as thanks to them, I improved so much,&quot; Barral states.</p>
				<p>Visceral Manipulation is just a part of the osteopathic therapeutic arsenal. It does not make sense to say that one specializes in cranial, vertebral or peripheral joints. The osteopathic concept demands to see a man in his globalism. It's for this reason Barral has always refused &quot;the stamp of a visceralist&quot;. He used to jokingly say, &quot;Maybe one day we will see a right foot specialist and another specialist for the left foot&quot;</p>
				<p><strong><em>A High Manual Precision</em></strong><br />
					In the 1970's Jean-Pierre Barral, Jean-Paul Mathieu and Pierre Mercier worked with Doctor Gillet, a Chiropractor, to analyze and treat the spine according to very precise ligamentous directions. Bernard Jularet, an Osteopath who passed away at a very young age, also helped in the research. Together they wrote one of the first French books about Osteopathy titled &quot;The Articular Vertebral Diagnosis.&quot;</p>
